<title>FOAM Build</title>
<h1>Pom-O-Matic</h1>
<p>Solve your Build troubles with Pom-O-Matic!</p>

<h1>Overview</h1>

<p>The FOAM build is a <b>node</b> tool which executes Javascript methods (<b>Tasks</b>) against Project Object Model (<b>POM</b>)(or a more lighthearted acronym expansion: Pom-O-Matic) files.</p>


<p><b>POMs</b> are JSON files which identify source code, application configuration, and build instructions. They are hierarchical and can exist at any level of a code repository.</p>

<p>There are two types of POMs:
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - POMs which configure the Build environment itself. <i>For example</i>, preparing for a Java build.</li>
  <li><b>Build</b> - POMs which specify code and deployment configuration to include.  <i>For example</i>, specifying the models to generate Java from and specifying the configuration to include in a JAR file.</li>
</ol>
</p>

<p>There are three distinct build <b>phases</b>:
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - the build loads Tooling POMs which add evironment variables (<b>envs</b>), command line options (<b>args</b>), and build <b>Tasks</b> specific to the type of code generation, compilation, and deployment to be supported.  <i>For example</i>, <b>JavaTooling</b> adds variables to control the Java target version, adds command line arguments to control creating a JAR file or start the JVM with JDPA enabled, adds Tasks for building and starting from JAR file locally or building a TAR file for remote deployment.
  </li>
  <li><b>Environment and Registration</b> - the build processes the Build POMs to (1) set environment variable values for variables added during the Tooling phase (i.e., Java target release = 21), and (2) register Build POM <b>Tasks</b> to be run when same-named Tooling <b>Tasks</b> are run (i.e., <b>setJavaEnv</b> JAVA_OPTS=-Dxyz before the JVM is started).
  </li>
  <li><b>Task</b> - the build processes the command line arguments, for options added during the Tooling phase, and prepares a set of <b>Tasks</b> which are then executed.  The <b>Tasks</b> themselves, act on the Build POMs.
  </li>
</ol>
</p>


